{"title_page": "Richard Hake", "text_new": "{{short description|News host and reported for WNYC}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Richard Hake\n| partner = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| alma_mater = Fordham University\n| period = \n| genre = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement = \n| notableworks = <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| children = \n| citizenship = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| education = \n| nationality = \n| embed = \n| native_name = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name_lang = \n| language = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1969|01|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Bronx]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|04|24|1969|01|23}}\n| death_place = New York City\n| resting_place = \n| occupation = \n| portaldisp = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n'''Richard Hake''' (January 4, 1969 \u2013 April 24, 2020) was a journalist and reporter for [[WNYC]], where he was one of the hosts of the weekly morning program, ''[[Morning Edition]]''. \n\n== Biography\u00a0==\n[[File:WNYC-Logo.svg|thumb|[[WNYC]], New York Public Radio, where Richard Hake worked for 29 years.]]\nRichard Scott Hake was born in the Bronx on January 4, 1969 to Richard James Hake, a New York City police detective, and Joy Mekland, a clerical worker and secretary.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hake had two brothers and one sister.<ref name=\":0\" /> He graduated from [[Fordham University]] in 1991, and began working at NPR in 1991 while still at Fordham.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Taylor|first=Derrick Bryson|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/25/nyregion/richard-hake-dead.html|title=Richard Hake, Longtime WNYC Radio Reporter and Host, Dies at 51|date=2020-04-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Stewart|first=Alison|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/remembering-richard-hake-face-masks-games-reviewpreview-tribec-ish-kathy-valentine-good-vibes-aerial-photography|title=All of It with Alison Stewart: Remembering Richard Hake, Face Masks, Games Review/Preview, Tribec-ish, Kathy Valentine, Good Vibes, Aerial Photography|date=April 27, 2020|work=WNYC|access-date=April 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He became the News Host and Reporter at WNYC in 1992.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wnyc.org/people/richard-hake/|title=People - Richard Hake {{!}} WNYC {{!}} New York Public Radio, Podcasts, Live Streaming Radio, News|website=WNYC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref> He spent 28 years working as a radio news host, reporter, and producer.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/9d17cc4349bc3326bf82d62c043b6026|title=Richard Hake, longtime New York City radio host, dies at 51|date=2020-04-25|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref> He was openly gay.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nHe spent 30 years working as a radio news host, reporter, and producer.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was featured on several local and national NPR programs, such as [[Morning Edition|''Morning Edition'']] (which he hosted), [[Weekend Edition|''Weekend Edition'']], [[All Things Considered|''All Things Considered'']], and [[On the Media|''On the Media'']].<ref name=\":0\" /> He also broadcast on [[MTV]], [[BBC|the BBC]], [[WCBS (AM)|WCBS]], [[WBGO]], WOR, and [[WFUV]] Radio.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://trvproductions.com/richard-hake.html|title=Richard Hake|website=The Right Voice Productions, Inc.|language=en|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref> Hake hosted for MTV's Logo Network's The Advocate News magazine program.<ref name=\":3\" /> His documentary work includes \"The Perfume of the Bronx\" and the \"[[Coney Island Cyclone]] Anniversary.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFor his reporting, Hake was awarded accolades from The Associated Press Broadcasters Association and the [[Society of Professional Journalists]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Hake made his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut as a chimney sweep in ''[[Mary Poppins (musical)|Mary Poppins]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/178405-mary-poppins-day/|title=WNYC Host Richard Hake Makes Broadway Debut in \u2018Mary Poppins\u2019 {{!}} WNYC {{!}} New York Public Radio, Podcasts, Live Streaming Radio, News|last=Hake|first=Richard|date=December 30, 2011|website=WNYC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref> \n\nHake died of natural causes on April 24, 2020, at age 51, in his [[Upper East Side]] home.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gothamist.com/news/richard-hake-beloved-trusted-wnyc-anchor-dies-51 |title=Richard Hake, Beloved & Trusted WNYC Anchor, Dies At 51 |last=Robbins |first=Christopher |date=2020-04-25 |website=Gothamist |language=en |access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/richard-hake-1969-2020/|title=Richard Hake, 1969 - 2020 {{!}} WNYC {{!}} New York Public Radio, Podcasts, Live Streaming Radio, News|last=O'Grady|first=Jim|date=April 27, 2020|website=WNYC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.wnyc.org/ WNYC] - New York Public Radio\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hake, Richard}}\n\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:New York Public Radio]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Fordham University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n{{US-radio-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|News host and reported for WNYC}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name = Richard Hake\n| partner