m the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Guhagar had a population of 3205. Males constitute 52% of the population and females 48%. Guhagar has an average literacy rate of 82%, higher than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 86%, and female literacy is 78%. In Guhagar, 10% of the population is under 6 years of age.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Guhagar Beach (2008).jpg|View of Guhagar Beach\nFile:Durga Devi Temple.jpg|Durga Devi Temple\nFile:Shri Vyadweshwar, Guhagar.jpg|Pindi of Shri Vyadeshwar\nFile:Official shri vyadeshwar aarti.jpg|Shri Vyadeshwar Aarti\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Guhagar}}\n<references/>\n\n{{Ratnagiri district topics}}\n\n[[Category:Talukas in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Ratnagiri district]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Ratnagiri district]]\n", "name_user": "Sorabh12", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guhagar"}
{"title_page": "Sweat of the brow", "text_new": "{{For|the Jully Black song|Sweat of Your Brow}}\n{{Short description|Copyright law doctrine}}\n[[File:'The feast of reason, and the flow of soul,' - ie - the wits of the age, setting the table in a roar by James Gillray.jpg|thumb|right|300px|As [[James Gillray]], the artist of this 1797 etching, died in 1815, his works are in the [[public domain]] throughout the world. However, under the \"sweat of the brow\" doctrine, new copyright claims could be made over mechanical reproductions of the etching, due to the skill and labor involved in the reproduction.]]\n\n'''Sweat of the brow''' is an [[intellectual property]] [[Legal doctrine|law doctrine]], chiefly related to [[copyright]] law. According to this doctrine, an [[author]] gains rights through  simple diligence during the creation of a work, such as a database, or a directory. Substantial creativity or \"originality\" is not required.\n\nUnder a \"sweat of the brow\" doctrine, the creator of a work, even if it is completely unoriginal, is entitled to have that effort and expense protected; no one else may use such a work without permission, but must instead recreate the work by independent research or effort. The classic example is a [[telephone directory]]. In a \"sweat of the brow\" jurisdiction, such a directory may not be copied, but instead a competitor must independently collect the information to issue a competing directory. The same rule generally applies to databases and lists of facts.\n\n[[Civil law (legal system)|Civil law]] jurisdictions have traditionally used the similar but not identical concept of ''[[droit d'auteur]]''. [[European Union law]] tends to harmonize the protection of intellectual property throughout member states and the doctrine thus gains more influence. In the Databases Directive 96/9/EC{{emdash}}the [[Member State of the European Union|member states of the EU]] are obliged to confer protection known as the [[database right]] on non-original databases, that is on those that embody no creativity, but are a consequence of substantial investment (financial, labour etc.).<ref>[http://www.bonnanwalt.de/rg/internet/law/eu/RiLi96-9-eg.html EU Richtlinie 96/9/EG] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621055429/http://www.bonnanwalt.de/rg/internet/law/eu/RiLi96-9-eg.html |date=2007-06-21 }} {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nIn a traditional [[English language|English]] [[idiom]], the ''sweat of one's brow'' refers to the effort expended in labor, and the value created thereby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://machaut.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/WEBSTER.page.sh?page=1457|page=1457|access-date=2007-05-30|work=Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary (1913 ed)|title=Sweat, v. t.|publisher=ARTFL Project|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060303004057/http://machaut.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/WEBSTER.page.sh?page=1457|archive-date=2006-03-03|df=}}</ref> The phrase is famously used in English translations of {{sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Genesis|chapter=3|verse=19}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newlivingtranslation.com/05discoverthenlt/ssresults.asp?txtSearchString=Genesis+3|accessdate=2007-05-30|title=New Living Translation|publisher=Tyndale House Publishers, inc.|quote=By the sweat of your brow will you have food to eat}}</ref> The law doctrine takes its name from this idiom.\n\n==By territory==\n\n===United States===\n{{see also|Copyright law in the United States}}\nThe [[United States]] rejected this doctrine in the 1991 [[United States Supreme Court]] case ''[[Feist Publications v. Rural Telephone Service]]'';<ref>{{ussc|499|340|1991}}</ref> until then it had been upheld in a number of US copyright cases.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Leaffer |first=Marshall A. |translator-last=\u7267\u91ce (Makino) |translator-first=\u548c\u592b (Kazuo) |title=\u30a2\u30e1\u30ea\u30ab\u8457\u4f5c\u6a29\u6cd5 |trans-title=Understanding Copyright Law (4th edition) |publisher=[[LexisNexis]] Japan |year=2008 |orig-year=2005 |p=94 |postscript=--Chapter 2 Article 12-B |isbn=978-4-8419-0509-0 |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=\u5c71\u672c (Yamamoto) |first=\u9686\u53f8 (Takashi B.) |title=\u30a2\u30e1\u30ea\u30ab\u8457\u4f5c\u6a29\u6cd5\u306e\u57fa\u790e\u77e5\u8b58 |trans-title=The Fundamentals of American Copyright Law |publisher=\u592a\u7530\u51fa\u7248 (Ohta Books) |series=\u30e6\u30cb\u77e5\u7684\u6240\u6709\u6a29\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u30b99 (UNI IP Books 9) |year=2008 |edition=2 |isbn=978-4-7783-1112-4 |language=ja |quote=\u7c73\u56fd\u8457\u4f5c\u6a29\u6cd5\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u5275\u4f5c\u6027\u306e\u6982\u5ff5\u306f\u3001\u305d\u306e\u5f8c\u4e0b\u7d1a\u88c1\u5224\u6240\u306e\u63a1\u7528\u3057\u305f\u984d\u306e\u6c57 (sweat of the brow) \u306e\u7406\u8ad6\u306b\u3088\u3063\u3066\u4e00\u6642\u6df7\u4e71\u3057\u305f\u3002\u3057\u304b\u3057\u3001\u7d0490\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u306b\u9023\u90a6\u6700\u9ad8\u88c1\u304c\u5275\u4f5c\u6027\u306e\u6982\u5ff5\u3092\u8ad6\u3058\u305f1991\u5e74\u306e\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30b9\u30c8\u5224\u6c7a\u306f\u3001\u6b21\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306b\u8ff0\u3079\u3066\u3001\u4e0a\u8a18\u306e\u4f1d\u7d71\u7684\u7406\u89e3\u3092\u78ba\u8a8d\u3057\u305f\u3002(translation: The definition of Originality had been disturbed by the sweat of the brow doctrine adopted by lower courts. After almost 90 years from the 1903 Bleistein case, however, the Supreme Court reaffirmed the traditional understanding of the Originality at the Feist case in 1991.)}}</ref>\n\nUnder the ''Feist'' ruling in the US, mere collections of facts are considered unoriginal and thus not protected by copyright, no matter how much work went into [[collation|collating]] them. The arrangement and presentation of a collection may be original, but not if it is \"simple and obvious\" such as a list in [[alphabetical]] or [[chronological]] order.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nUnder the [[Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988]], for copyright to subsist in a work, that work must be original. However, courts have not adopted a literal reading of this requirement. For over a hundred years, English courts have held that a significant expenditure of labour is sufficient. The consequence of this is that if A makes a work in which copyright subsists, and B subsequently adds his skill, judgement and labour, altering the form of A's work, B will potentially have a copyright in the work he produces. This suggests that copyright is not about protecting ideas, because one can acquire a copyright by expending skill, labour, and judgement, but no creativity or inventiveness.\n\nHowever, in March 2012, a case was taken to the [[European Court of Justice]], in which [[Football DataCo]] claimed [[copyright infringement]] over web sites which were reproducing match schedules from several major [[association football|football]] leagues. Football DataCo asserted that these schedules were copyrighted works due to the skill and labour involved in their preparation, and that the company was given exclusive rights to license their reproduction. Based on its interpretation of British law, the court rejected the notion that labour and skill was enough to grant protection to a work, since \"unless the procedures for creating the lists concerned as described by the national court are supplemented by elements reflecting originality in the selection or arrangement of the data contained in those lists, they do not suffice for those lists to be protected by the copyright laid down in the directive.\"<ref name=bbcn-dataco>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Bill|title=Football match fixture list copyright claim rejected|date=March 2012|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-17218968|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a copyright notice on \"digital images, photographs and the internet\" last updated in November 2015, the UK [[Intellectual Property Office (United Kingdom)|Intellectual Property Office]] confirmed that digital reproductions of [[public domain]] images are not protected by copyright, arguing that \"according to the Court of Justice of the European Union which has effect in UK law, copyright can only subsist in subject matter that is original in the sense that it is the author's own \"intellectual creation\". Given this criterion, it seems unlikely that what is merely a retouched, digitised image of an older work can be considered as \"original\".\"<ref name=IPO-cnote>{{cite web|author=UK Intellectual Property Office|title=Copyright Notice: digital images, photographs and the internet|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/481194/c-notice-201401.pdf|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Examples====\nIn ''[[Walter v Lane]]'' (1900) (Pre-CDPA), reporters took shorthand notes of a speech, punctuated them, etc. and published them in the [[The Times|''Times'']] newspaper. The court held that the reporters were authors of the published speech, and, as such, owned a copyright in the published speeches, because of the considerable skill, labour, and judgement they exercised.\n\nIn ''[[University of London Press Ltd v University Tutorial Press Ltd]]'',<ref>University of London Press v University Tutorial [1916] 2 Ch 601</ref> the question arose as to whether certain mathematics exam papers were original literary works. The exam papers just consisted of conventional maths problems in a conventional manner. The court held that originality does not mean that the work must be an expression of individual thought. The simple fact that the authors drew on a body of knowledge common to mathematicians did not compromise originality. The requirement of originality, it was held, does not require that expression be in an original or novel form. It does, however, require that the work not be copied from another work. It must originate from the author.\nAs such, even though these were the same old maths problems every student is familiar with, and even though there was no creative input, the skill, labour, and judgement of the authors was sufficient to make the papers original literary works.\n\nIn ''[[Cummins v Bond]]'', a psychic in a trance claimed to have written down what spirits told her, through a process of [[automatic writing]]. In court, she accepted that she was not the creative author of the writing. The creative input, had, presumably, come from the spirits.<ref>{{cite web|author=William Patry |url=http://williampatry.blogspot.gr/2005/08/authorship-and-religion.html |title=The Patry Copyright Blog: Authorship and Religion |publisher=Williampatry.blogspot.gr |date=2005-08-10 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> Nonetheless, the court held that she had exercised sufficient labour and skill in translating and transcribing what the spirits told her, so she had a copyright in the resulting literary work.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nIn 2013, [[Ministry of Sound]] sued the subscription music-streaming service [[Spotify]] over user-created playlists mimicking the track listings of their [[Compilation album|compilation albums]], alleging that they infringed the copyright of the albums themselves due to the skill and effort in their creation.<ref>{{cite web |first=Joe |last=Mullin |title=Spotify sued over user playlists, said to infringe copyright |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/09/spotify-sued-over-user-playlists-said-to-infringe-copyright/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Stuart |last=Dredge |title=Ministry of Sound sues Spotify for copyright infringement |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/sep/04/ministry-of-sound-sues-spotify |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref> The parties settled in 2014 without going to trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/feb/27/spotify-ministry-of-sound-lawsuit-settlement|title=Spotify and Ministry of Sound settle music playlists copyright lawsuit|last=Dredge|first=Stuart|date=2014-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nIn certain cases, German law grants ancillary copyrights (''Leistungsschutzrecht'') due to the effort involved in the production or exploitation of creative works.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nolte|first1=Georg|title=Zur Forderung der Presseverleger nach Einf\u00fchrung eines speziellen Leistungsschutzrechts: Eine kritische Auseinandersetzung|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Geistiges Eigentum|date=1 July 2010|volume=2|issue=2|pages=165\u2013195|doi=10.1628/186723710792175149|language=de}}</ref> In 2016, a [[Landgericht Berlin|regional court in Berlin]] ruled that digitized versions of public domain paintings were entitled to new copyrights due to the effort and expertise necessary to create the reproductions. The case was appealed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moody|first1=Glyn|title=Digitising public domain images creates a new copyright, rules German court [Updated]|url=http://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2016/06/digitising-public-domain-images-creates-a-new-copyright-germany/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=5 July 2016|date=23 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite court|litigants=Reiss-Engelhorn Museum (REM) of the City of Mannheim v. Wikimedia Foundation|url=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/foundation/5/52/Reiss-Engelhorn_Museum_%28REM%29_of_the_City_of_Mannheim_v._Wikimedia_Foundation_Landgericht.pdf|court=Landgericht Berlin|date=2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> In 2018 a court upheld the decision that the digitized public domain paintings were entitled to new copyrights.<ref name=\"Bundesgerichtshof 2018-12-20\">{{cite press release |url=https://juris.bundesgerichtshof.de/cgi-bin/rechtsprechung/document.py?Gericht=bgh&Art=pm&Datum=2018&Sort=3&nr=90674&pos=1&anz=195 |title=Bundesgerichtshof zur Ver\u00f6ffentlichung von Fotografien gemeinfreier Kunstwerke |language=de |location=Karlsruhe Germany |publisher=Bundesgerichtshof |date=2018-12-20 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621091457/https://juris.bundesgerichtshof.de/cgi-bin/rechtsprechung/document.py?Gericht=bgh&Art=pm&Datum=2018&Sort=3&nr=90674&pos=1&anz=195 |archivedate=2019-06-21 |accessdate=2020-01-26 }}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\nIn 2019, the [[European Union]] adopted the [[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market]]. Article 14 of the directive states that reproductions of works of visual art that are in the public domain cannot be subject to copyright or related rights, unless the reproduction is an original creative work.<ref name=\"finaltext\">{{cite web |title=Final text of the Directive as submitted to the Parliament on 26 March 2019|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf |accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nIsraeli law requires that a work exhibit some [[threshold of originality|degree of originality]] in order to be copyrightable. In other words, Israeli law does not subscribe to the \"sweat of the brow\" doctrine.<ref>Tempska, Urzula (2002). [http://scholarship.law.marquette.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1036&context=iplr \"'Originality' After the Dead Sea Scrolls Decision: Implications for the American Law of Copyright\"]. ''Marquette Intellectual Property Law Review'' '''6''' (1): 132.</ref> However, the amount of originality required is minimal, and the transliteration or interpretation of an artifact is covered by copyright.<ref>Elkin-Koren, Niva (2001). [http://www.houstonlawreview.org/archive/downloads/38-2_pdf/HLR38P445.pdf \"Of Scientific Claims and Proprietary Rights: Lessons from the Dead Sea Scrolls\"], ''Houston Law Review'' '''38''' (2): 458, 460.</ref>\n\n===Uruguay===\nUruguayan law requires that the work should have some degree of originality to be protected by copyright. Uruguayan law, therefore, does not subscribe to the sweat of the brow doctrine.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Copyfraud]]\n*[[Liberalism#Classical and modern|Lockean Classical liberalism]]\n*[[Labour theory of value]]\n*[[Database right]]\n*[[Sweat equity]]\n*[[Threshold of originality]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Intellectual property law]]\n[[Category:Copyright law]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Jully Black song|Sweat of Your Brow}}\n{{Short description|Copyright law doctrine}}\n[[File:'The feast of reason, and the flow of soul,' - ie - the wits of the age, setting the table in a roar by James Gillray.jpg|thumb|right|300px|As [[James Gillray]], the artist of this 1797 etching, died in 1815, his works are in the [[public domain]] throughout the world. However, under the \"sweat of the brow\" doctrine, new copyright claims could be made over mechanical reproductions of the etching, due to the skill and labor involved in the reproduction.]]\n\n'''Sweat of the brow''' is an [[intellectual property]] [[Legal doctrine|law doctrine]], chiefly related to [[copyright]] law. According to this doctrine, an [[author]] gains rights through  simple diligence during the creation of a work, such as a database, or a directory. Substantial creativity or \"originality\" is not required.\n\nUnder a \"sweat of the brow\" doctrine, the creator of a work, even if it is completely unoriginal, is entitled to have that effort and expense protected; no one else may use such a work without permission, but must instead recreate the work by independent research or effort. The classic example is a [[telephone directory]]. In a \"sweat of the brow\" jurisdiction, such a directory may not be copied, but instead a competitor must independently collect the information to issue a competing directory. The same rule generally applies to databases and lists of facts.\n\n[[Civil law (legal system)|Civil law]] jurisdictions have traditionally used the similar but not identical concept of ''[[droit d'auteur]]''. [[European Union law]] tends to harmonize the protection of intellectual property throughout member states and the doctrine thus gains more influence. In the Databases Directive 96/9/EC{{emdash}}the [[Member State of the European Union|member states of the EU]] are obliged to confer protection known as the [[database right]] on non-original databases, that is on those that embody no creativity, but are a consequence of substantial investment (financial, labour etc.).<ref>[http://www.bonnanwalt.de/rg/internet/law/eu/RiLi96-9-eg.html EU Richtlinie 96/9/EG] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621055429/http://www.bonnanwalt.de/rg/internet/law/eu/RiLi96-9-eg.html |date=2007-06-21 }} {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nIn a traditional [[English language|English]] [[idiom]], the ''sweat of one's brow'' refers to the effort expended in labor, and the value created thereby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://machaut.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/WEBSTER.page.sh?page=1457|page=1457|access-date=2007-05-30|work=Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary (1913 ed)|title=Sweat, v. t.|publisher=ARTFL Project|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060303004057/http://machaut.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/WEBSTER.page.sh?page=1457|archive-date=2006-03-03|df=}}</ref> The phrase is famously used in English translations of {{sourcetext|source=Bible|version=King James|book=Genesis|chapter=3|verse=19}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newlivingtranslation.com/05discoverthenlt/ssresults.asp?txtSearchString=Genesis+3|accessdate=2007-05-30|title=New Living Translation|publisher=Tyndale House Publishers, inc.|quote=By the sweat of your brow will you have food to eat}}</ref> The law doctrine takes its name from this idiom.\n\n==By territory==\n\n===United States===\n{{see also|Copyright law in the United States}}\nThe [[United States]] rejected this doctrine in the 1991 [[United States Supreme Court]] case ''[[Feist Publications v. Rural Telephone Service]]'';<ref>{{ussc|499|340|1991}}</ref> until then it had been upheld in a number of US copyright cases.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Leaffer |first=Marshall A. |translator-last=\u7267\u91ce (Makino) |translator-first=\u548c\u592b (Kazuo) |title=\u30a2\u30e1\u30ea\u30ab\u8457\u4f5c\u6a29\u6cd5 |trans-title=Understanding Copyright Law (4th edition) |publisher=[[LexisNexis]] Japan |year=2008 |orig-year=2005 |p=94 |postscript=--Chapter 2 Article 12-B |isbn=978-4-8419-0509-0 |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=\u5c71\u672c (Yamamoto) |first=\u9686\u53f8 (Takashi B.) |title=\u30a2\u30e1\u30ea\u30ab\u8457\u4f5c\u6a29\u6cd5\u306e\u57fa\u790e\u77e5\u8b58 |trans-title=The Fundamentals of American Copyright Law |publisher=\u592a\u7530\u51fa\u7248 (Ohta Books) |series=\u30e6\u30cb\u77e5\u7684\u6240\u6709\u6a29\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u30b99 (UNI IP Books 9) |year=2008 |edition=2 |isbn=978-4-7783-1112-4 |language=ja |quote=\u7c73\u56fd\u8457\u4f5c\u6a29\u6cd5\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u5275\u4f5c\u6027\u306e\u6982\u5ff5\u306f\u3001\u305d\u306e\u5f8c\u4e0b\u7d1a\u88c1\u5224\u6240\u306e\u63a1\u7528\u3057\u305f\u984d\u306e\u6c57 (sweat of the brow) \u306e\u7406\u8ad6\u306b\u3088\u3063\u3066\u4e00\u6642\u6df7\u4e71\u3057\u305f\u3002\u3057\u304b\u3057\u3001\u7d0490\u5e74\u3076\u308a\u306b\u9023\u90a6\u6700\u9ad8\u88c1\u304c\u5275\u4f5c\u6027\u306e\u6982\u5ff5\u3092\u8ad6\u3058\u305f1991\u5e74\u306e\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30b9\u30c8\u5224\u6c7a\u306f\u3001\u6b21\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306b\u8ff0\u3079\u3066\u3001\u4e0a\u8a18\u306e\u4f1d\u7d71\u7684\u7406\u89e3\u3092\u78ba\u8a8d\u3057\u305f\u3002(translation: The definition of Originality had been disturbed by the sweat of the brow doctrine adopted by lower courts. After almost 90 years from the 1903 Bleistein case, however, the Supreme Court reaffirmed the traditional understanding of the Originality at the Feist case in 1991.)}}</ref>\n\nUnder the ''Feist'' ruling in the US, mere collections of facts are considered unoriginal and thus not protected by copyright, no matter how much work went into [[collation|collating]] them. The arrangement and presentation of a collection may be original, but not if it is \"simple and obvious\" such as a list in [[alphabetical]] or [[chronological]] order.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nUnder the [[Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988]], for copyright to subsist in a work, that work must be original. However, courts have not adopted a literal reading of this requirement. For over a hundred years, English courts have held that a significant expenditure of labour is sufficient. The consequence of this is that if A makes a work in which copyright subsists, and B subsequently adds his skill, judgement and labour, altering the form of A's work, B will potentially have a copyright in the work he produces. This suggests that copyright is not about protecting ideas, because one can acquire a copyright by expending skill, labour, and judgement, but no creativity or inventiveness.\n\nHowever, in March 2012, a case was taken to the [[European Court of Justice]], in which [[Football DataCo]] claimed [[copyright infringement]] over web sites which were reproducing match schedules from several major [[association football|football]] leagues. Football DataCo asserted that these schedules were copyrighted works due to the skill and labour involved in their preparation, and that the company was given exclusive rights to license their reproduction. Based on its interpretation of British law, the court rejected the notion that labour and skill was enough to grant protection to a work, since \"unless the procedures for creating the lists concerned as described by the national court are supplemented by elements reflecting originality in the selection or arrangement of the data contained in those lists, they do not suffice for those lists to be protected by the copyright laid down in the directive.\"<ref name=bbcn-dataco>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Bill|title=Football match fixture list copyright claim rejected|date=March 2012|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-17218968|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a copyright notice on 'digital images, photographs and the internet' last updated in November 2015, the UK [[Intellectual Property Office (United Kingdom)|Intellectual Property Office]] confirmed that digital reproductions of [[public domain]] images are not protected by copyright, arguing that \"according to the Court of Justice of the European Union which has effect in UK law, copyright can only subsist in subject matter that is original in the sense that it is the author\u2019s own \u2018intellectual creation\u2019. Given this criterion, it seems unlikely that what is merely a retouched, digitised image of an older work can be considered as \u2018original\u2019.\"<ref name=IPO-cnote>{{cite web|author=UK Intellectual Property Office|title=Copyright Notice: digital images, photographs and the internet|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/481194/c-notice-201401.pdf|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Examples====\nIn ''[[Walter v Lane]]'' (1900) (Pre-CDPA), reporters took shorthand notes of a speech, punctuated them, etc. and published them in the [[The Times|''Times'']] newspaper. The court held that the reporters were authors of the published speech, and, as such, owned a copyright in the published speeches, because of the considerable skill, labour, and judgement they exercised.\n\nIn ''[[University of London Press Ltd v University Tutorial Press Ltd]]'',<ref>University of London Press v University Tutorial [1916] 2 Ch 601</ref> the question arose as to whether certain mathematics exam papers were original literary works. The exam papers just consisted of conventional maths problems in a conventional manner. The court held that originality does not mean that the work must be an expression of individual thought. The simple fact that the authors drew on a body of knowledge common to mathematicians did not compromise originality. The requirement of originality, it was held, does not require that expression be in an original or novel form. It does, however, require that the work not be copied from another work. It must originate from the author.\nAs such, even though these were the same old maths problems every student is familiar with, and even though there was no creative input, the skill, labour, and judgement of the authors was sufficient to make the papers original literary works.\n\nIn ''[[Cummins v Bond]]'', a psychic in a trance claimed to have written down what spirits told her, through a process of [[automatic writing]]. In court, she accepted that she was not the creative author of the writing. The creative input, had, presumably, come from the spirits.<ref>{{cite web|author=William Patry |url=http://williampatry.blogspot.gr/2005/08/authorship-and-religion.html |title=The Patry Copyright Blog: Authorship and Religion |publisher=Williampatry.blogspot.gr |date=2005-08-10 |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref> Nonetheless, the court held that she had exercised sufficient labour and skill in translating and transcribing what the spirits told her, so she had a copyright in the resulting literary work.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nIn 2013, [[Ministry of Sound]] sued the subscription music-streaming service [[Spotify]] over user-created playlists mimicking the track listings of their [[Compilation album|compilation albums]], alleging that they infringed the copyright of the albums themselves due to the skill and effort in their creation.<ref>{{cite web |first=Joe |last=Mullin |title=Spotify sued over user playlists, said to infringe copyright |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/09/spotify-sued-over-user-playlists-said-to-infringe-copyright/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Stuart |last=Dredge |title=Ministry of Sound sues Spotify for copyright infringement |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/sep/04/ministry-of-sound-sues-spotify |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref> The parties settled in 2014 without going to trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/feb/27/spotify-ministry-of-sound-lawsuit-settlement|title=Spotify and Ministry of Sound settle music playlists copyright lawsuit|last=Dredge|first=Stuart|date=2014-02-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nIn certain cases, German law grants ancillary copyrights (''Leistungsschutzrecht'') due to the effort involved in the production or exploitation of creative works.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nolte|first1=Georg|title=Zur Forderung der Presseverleger nach Einf\u00fchrung eines speziellen Leistungsschutzrechts: Eine kritische Auseinandersetzung|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Geistiges Eigentum|date=1 July 2010|volume=2|issue=2|pages=165\u2013195|doi=10.1628/186723710792175149|language=de}}</ref> In 2016, a [[Landgericht Berlin|regional court in Berlin]] ruled that digitized versions of public domain paintings were entitled to new copyrights due to the effort and expertise necessary to create the reproductions. The case was appealed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moody|first1=Glyn|title=Digitising public domain images creates a new copyright, rules German court [Updated]|url=http://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2016/06/digitising-public-domain-images-creates-a-new-copyright-germany/|website=Ars Technica UK|accessdate=5 July 2016|date=23 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite court|litigants=Reiss-Engelhorn Museum (REM) of the City of Mannheim v. Wikimedia Foundation|url=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/foundation/5/52/Reiss-Engelhorn_Museum_%28REM%29_of_the_City_of_Mannheim_v._Wikimedia_Foundation_Landgericht.pdf|court=Landgericht Berlin|date=2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> In 2018 a court upheld the decision that the digitized public domain paintings were entitled to new copyrights.<ref name=\"Bundesgerichtshof 2018-12-20\">{{cite press release |url=https://juris.bundesgerichtshof.de/cgi-bin/rechtsprechung/document.py?Gericht=bgh&Art=pm&Datum=2018&Sort=3&nr=90674&pos=1&anz=195 |title=Bundesgerichtshof zur Ver\u00f6ffentlichung von Fotografien gemeinfreier Kunstwerke |language=de |location=Karlsruhe Germany |publisher=Bundesgerichtshof |date=2018-12-20 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621091457/https://juris.bundesgerichtshof.de/cgi-bin/rechtsprechung/document.py?Gericht=bgh&Art=pm&Datum=2018&Sort=3&nr=90674&pos=1&anz=195 |archivedate=2019-06-21 |accessdate=2020-01-26 }}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\nIn 2019, the [[European Union]] adopted the [[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market]]. Article 14 of the directive states that reproductions of works of visual art that are in the public domain cannot be subject to copyright or related rights, unless the reproduction is an original creative work.<ref name=\"finaltext\">{{cite web |title=Final text of the Directive as submitted to the Parliament on 26 March 2019|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/A-8-2018-0245-AM-271-271_EN.pdf |accessdate=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\nIsraeli law requires that a work exhibit some [[threshold of originality|degree of originality]] in order to be copyrightable. In other words, Israeli law does not subscribe to the \"sweat of the brow\" doctrine.<ref>Tempska, Urzula (2002). [http://scholarship.law.marquette.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1036&context=iplr \"'Originality' After the Dead Sea Scrolls Decision: Implications for the American Law of Copyright\"]. ''Marquette Intellectual Property Law Review'' '''6''' (1): 132.</ref> However, the amount of originality required is minimal, and the transliteration or interpretation of an artifact is covered by copyright.<ref>Elkin-Koren, Niva (2001). [http://www.houstonlawreview.org/archive/downloads/38-2_pdf/HLR38P445.pdf \"Of Scientific Claims and Proprietary Rights: Lessons from the Dead Sea Scrolls\"], ''Houston Law Review'' '''38''' (2): 458, 460.</ref>\n\n===Uruguay===\nUruguayan law requires that the work should have some degree of originality to be protected by copyright. Uruguayan law, therefore, does not subscribe to the sweat of the brow doctrine.{{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Copyfraud]]\n*[[Liberalism#Classical and modern|Lockean Classical liberalism]]\n*[[Labour theory of value]]\n*[[Database right]]\n*[[Sweat equity]]\n*[[Threshold of originality]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Intellectual property law]]\n[[Category:Copyright law]]\n", "name_user": "GrindtXX", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited Kingdom:straight quotes, dble quotes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweat_of_the_brow"}
{"title_page": "Agusti Pol", "text_new": "{{short description|Andorran footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name=Agusti Pol\n|image=\n|fullname=\n|birth_date ={{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|1|13}}\n|birth_place=[[Andorra]]\n|death_date =\n|height=\n|position=[[Midfielder]] \n|currentclub=\n|clubnumber=\n|youthyears1=\n|youthclubs1=\n|years1=\n|clubs1=\n|caps1= | goals1 =\n|nationalyears1=1996\u20132003\n|nationalteam1=[[Andorra national football team|Andorra]]\n|nationalcaps1= 28 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n|manageryears1=\n|managerclubs1=\n}}\n'''Agusti Pol''' (born 13 January 1977) is an [[Andorra]]n [[Association football|football]] player. He has played for [[Andorra national football team|Andorra national team]]. His only goal for his country came in Andorra's first international match, a 6\u20131 defeat by [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 13 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last=Duret |first=S\u00e9bastien |title=Andorra - List of International Matches |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/ando-intres.html |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=13 November 2010 |date=26 April 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018113928/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/ando-intres.html |archivedate=18 October 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==National team statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Andorra national football team|Andorra national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|-\n|1996||1||1\n|-\n|1997||2||0\n|-\n|1998||7||0\n|-\n|1999||9||0\n|-\n|2000||0||0\n|-\n|2001||4||0\n|-\n|2002||4||0\n|-\n|2003||1||0\n|-\n!Total||28||1\n|}\n\n==International goal==\n:''Scores and results list Andorra's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 13 November 1996 || [[Estadi Comunal d'Andorra la Vella]], [[Andorra la Vella]], Andorra || {{fb|Estonia}} || '''1'''\u20131 || 1\u20136 || [[exhibition game|friendly match]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{NFT player|pid=172}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pol, Agusti}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Andorran footballers]]\n[[Category:Andorra international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Andorra players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n{{Andorra-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name=Agusti Pol\n|image=\n|fullname=\n|birth_date ={{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|1|13}}\n|birth_place=[[Andorra]]\n|death_date =\n|height=\n|position=[[Midfielder]] \n|currentclub=\n|clubnumber=\n|youthyears1=\n|youthclubs1=\n|years1=\n|clubs1=\n|caps1= | goals1 =\n|nationalyears1=1996\u20132003\n|nationalteam1=[[Andorra national football team|Andorra]]\n|nationalcaps1= 28 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n|manageryears1=\n|managerclubs1=\n}}\n'''Agusti Pol''' (born 13 January 1977) is an [[Andorra]]n [[Association football|football]] player. He has played for [[Andorra national football team|Andorra national team]]. His only goal for his country came in Andorra's first international match, a 6\u20131 defeat by [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 13 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last=Duret |first=S\u00e9bastien |title=Andorra - List of International Matches |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/ando-intres.html |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=13 November 2010 |date=26 April 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018113928/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/ando-intres.html |archivedate=18 October 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==National team statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Andorra national football team|Andorra national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|-\n|1996||1||1\n|-\n|1997||2||0\n|-\n|1998||7||0\n|-\n|1999||9||0\n|-\n|2000||0||0\n|-\n|2001||4||0\n|-\n|2002||4||0\n|-\n|2003||1||0\n|-\n!Total||28||1\n|}\n\n==International goal==\n:''Scores and results list Andorra's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 13 November 1996 || [[Estadi Comunal d'Andorra la Vella]], [[Andorra la Vella]], Andorra || {{fb|Estonia}} || '''1'''\u20131 || 1\u20136 || [[exhibition game|friendly match]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{NFT player|pid=172}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pol, Agusti}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Andorran footballers]]\n[[Category:Andorra international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Andorra players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n{{Andorra-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Andorran footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Andorran footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agusti_Pol"}
{"title_page": "Our Lady of Assumption Church, Pragasapuram", "text_new": "<br />{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Our Lady of Assumption Church, Pragasapuram\n| fullname               = \n| image                  = Rc Church Pragasapuram.jpg\n| imagesize              =\n\n| caption                = Our Lady of Assumption Church \n| latd                   = \n| latm                   = \n| lats                   = \n| latNS                  = \n| longd                  = \n| longm                  = \n| longs                  = \n| longEW                 = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|8.560715|77.971978|display=inline,title}}\n| location               = [[Pragasapuram]]\n| country                = [[India]]\n| denomination           = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| previous denomination  =\n| churchmanship          = \n| membership             = \n| attendance             = \n| website                = \n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| founded date           = 15th August 1880\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = \n| dedicated date         = \n| consecrated date       = 21st November 1967\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = Holy Mass, Eucharist\n| past bishop            = \n| people                 = \n| status                 = [[Parish Church]]\n| functional status      = Active\n| heritage designation   = Parish \n| designated date        = 1909\n| architect              = \n| architectural type     =\n| style                  = \n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      =\n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n| capacity               = \n| length                 = \n| width                  = \n| width nave             = \n| height                 = \n| diameter               = \n| other dimensions       = \n| floor count            = \n| floor area             = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           = \n| materials              = \n| parish                 = \n| deanery                = \n| archdeaconry           = \n| archdiocese            = \n| diocese                = \n| province               = \n| presbytery             = \n| synod                  = \n| circuit                = \n| district               = Tuticorin\n| division               = Sathankulam\n| subdivision            = Pragasapuram\n| archbishop             = \n| bishop                 = [[Most.Rev.Dr.A.Stephen]]\n| dean                   = \n| subdean                = \n| provost                = \n| provost-rector         = \n| viceprovost            = \n| canon                  = \n| canonpastor            = \n| precentor              = \n| archdeacon             = \n| prebendary             = \n| rector                 = \n| vicar                  = \n| curate                 = \n| priestincharge         = Fr.Antony Irudhaya Thomas\n| asstpriest             = \n| minister               = \n| assistant              = \n| honpriest              = \n| deacon                 = \n| deaconness             = \n| seniorpastor           = \n| pastor                 = \n| abbot                  = \n| chaplain               = \n| reader                 = \n| organistdom            = \n| director               = \n| organist               = \n| organscholar           = \n| chapterclerk           = \n| laychapter             = \n| warden                 = \n| flowerguild            = \n| musicgroup             = \n| parishadmin            = \n| serversguild           = \n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n}}\n\n'''Our Lady of Assumption Church'''  is a Roman Catholic church.It is the [[Parish]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]. And it has 7 Sub-Parishes.\n\n= History =\nHistory states that in 1979 there were 14 Catholic families in [[Pragasapuram]]. Initially Pragasapuram was the Sub-Parish of the Sathankulam Parish. In 15-08-1880, Our Lady of Assumption Chapel was opened by Fr.Denish Kushan. The first Car Procession of Our Lady of Assumption was held on 15-08-1895. At that time there was 3 Chapparam. Devotees carry it on their shoulders. In 1907, [[Arthur Margoschis]] (Father of Nazareth) presented the Holy Cross of Jesus Christ that he kept in his Prayer hall,\u00a0 to the Our Lady of Assumption Church, Pragasapuram. \n\nIn 1909, Pragasapuram became an independent Parish. Sub-Parishes separated from the [[Sathankulam]] and [[Punnaikayal]] Parishes were merged with the Pragasapuram Parish. The foundation stone for New Church was laid in 1913 by Fr.T.Michael. After the completion of the New Church foundation work, the Church building work was stopped. Thus the Holy Mass was conducted in the Old Our Lady of Assumption Chapel. Many years later the New Church was built and the New Church was opened by Bishop.Rev.Fr.Thomas on 21-11-1967.As the days went by, In 1975 during Fr.Cruz Mariyan period, Chapparam was replaced by Chariot. In the feasts that followed, the devotees\u00a0 celebrated the Annual Feast of Our Lady of Assumption by pulling the St.Mary's Chariot.\n\nSt. Mary's Kebi was built on 11-08-1980 at the site of the Old Our Lady of Assumption Chapel to commemorate the Century year (1880- 1980) of Our Lady of Assumption Chapel. The new Church altar was refurbished and the floors replaced with marbles when Fr.Jackson was a Parish Priest. In the 25th year of the construction of the St.Mary's Century Kebi, it was restored and renovated by Fr.A.S.Raja on 14-08-2007\n\n= Sub Parishes =\n\n1. Our Lady of Good Health Church, Madhavanam\n\n2. St.Joseph's Church, Kandhasamypuram\n\n3. Sacred Heart of Jesus Church, Pillayanmanai\n\n4. Our Lady of Lourdes Church, Udayarkulam\n\n5. Our Lady of Lourdes Church, Thoppur\n\n6. St. Antony's Church, Themankulam\n\n7. St. Antony's Church, Kurippankulam\n\n= Festivals =\n\n== St.Mary's Annual Feast ==\n\n[[File:Flag pole of olap.jpeg|thumb|right|Flagpole of Church]]\nThe Church Parish is celebrating the Our Lady of Assumption Annual Feast in a grand manner. St.Mary's Flag hoisting was held on 6 August every year. Followed by that they celebrating the festival for 10 days. 9th and 10th day of Feast is an Important day of Our Lady of Assumption.\n[[File:Olap chariot.jpeg|thumb|right|St.Mary's Chariot]]\nCar procession was held on 14th and 15 August every year. On 9th day of Feast Eucharistic Adoration service was held at the Church premises.On 10th day of Feast the Grand Holy Mass was held at the Church. Flag Lowering was held on end of the Feast (15 August Night).\n\n== Samabanthi ==\nChurch provides free food for all people thrice a year in following dates.\n\n1. First Saturday of May month\n\n2. 16 August\n\n3. 29 September\n\n== Christmas ==\nThey celebrate Christmas by conducting Carols and Holy Mass. They built a Christmas Crib inside the church that reminds the Birth of Jesus.\n\n== Easter == \nThey celebrate Easter by conducting a Holy Mass on 12:00 am.They placed a Resurrection of Jesus statue to reminds the Resurrection of Jesus.\n\n= Chapels = \n1. St. Mary's Chapel\n[[File:Arputha kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|St.Mary's Chapel]]\n2. St. Antony's Chapel\n[[File:Antony kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|St. Antony's Chapel]]\n3. St. Michael's Chapel\n[[File:Michael kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|St. Michael's Chapel]]\n4. Our Lady of Good Health Chapel \n[[File:Velankanni kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|Our Lady of Good Health Chapel]]\n\n= Schools =\nTotally 4 schools were managed by our Parish.\n\n1. St.Mary's Middle School, Pragasapuram \n\n2. St. Joseph Primary School, Kandasamipuram\n\n3. R.C. Primary School, Thoppur\n\n4. R.C. Primary School, Udayarkulam \n\n= Wedding Hall =\n\n[[File:Marys mahal.jpeg|thumb|right|St.Mary's Mahal]]\nIt was a long-standing desire of the Pragasapuram Parish peoples to have a Wedding Hall of our own. As a result, in 2003 the foundation work was started by Fr. Arul Jackson. Most.Rev.Bishop.Yuvon Ambrose laid the foundation stone for St. Mary's Mahal. The pillars were erected and the concrete work was completed in Fr.Arul Jackson period. During the period of Fr.A.S.Raja, the First Floor was completed. Fr. Antony Duglas completed the St. Mary's  Mahal project with his efforts. Afterwards, during St.Mary's Annual Feast on 15-08-2013 Most.Rev.Bishop.Yuvon Ambrose blessed the Mahal and Aachi Masala Founder Mr.A.D. Padmasingh Isac opened the St. Mary's Mahal.\n\n= Convent =\nServite Convent, Pragasapuram\n[[Category:Catholic Church]]\n\n= Reference =\n<ref>http://catholicchurches.in/directory/tuticorin-churches/our-lady-of-assumption-church-pragasapuram.htm  </ref>\n", "text_old": "<br />{{Infobox church\n| name                   = Our Lady of Assumption Church, Pragasapuram\n| fullname               = \n| image                  = Rc Church Pragasapuram.jpg\n| imagesize              =\n\n| caption                = Our Lady of Assumption Church \n| latd                   = \n| latm                   = \n| lats                   = \n| latNS                  = \n| longd                  = \n| longm                  = \n| longs                  = \n| longEW                 = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|8.560715|77.971978|display=inline,title}}\n| location               = [[Pragasapuram]]\n| country                = [[India]]\n| denomination           = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| previous denomination  =\n| churchmanship          = \n| membership             = \n| attendance             = \n| website                = \n| former name            = \n| bull date              = \n| founded date           = 15th August 1880\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = \n| dedicated date         = \n| consecrated date       = 21st November 1967\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = Holy Mass, Eucharist\n| past bishop            = \n| people                 = \n| status                 = [[Parish Church]]\n| functional status      = Active\n| heritage designation   = Parish \n| designated date        = 1909\n| architect              = \n| architectural type     =\n| style                  = \n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      =\n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n| capacity               = \n| length                 = \n| width                  = \n| width nave             = \n| height                 = \n| diameter               = \n| other dimensions       = \n| floor count            = \n| floor area             = \n| spire quantity         = \n| spire height           = \n| materials              = \n| parish                 = \n| deanery                = \n| archdeaconry           = \n| archdiocese            = \n| diocese                = \n| province               = \n| presbytery             = \n| synod                  = \n| circuit                = \n| district               = Tuticorin\n| division               = Sathankulam\n| subdivision            = Pragasapuram\n| archbishop             = \n| bishop                 = [[Most.Rev.Dr.A.Stephen]]\n| dean                   = \n| subdean                = \n| provost                = \n| provost-rector         = \n| viceprovost            = \n| canon                  = \n| canonpastor            = \n| precentor              = \n| archdeacon             = \n| prebendary             = \n| rector                 = \n| vicar                  = \n| curate                 = \n| priestincharge         = Fr.Antony Irudhaya Thomas\n| asstpriest             = \n| minister               = \n| assistant              = \n| honpriest              = \n| deacon                 = \n| deaconness             = \n| seniorpastor           = \n| pastor                 = \n| abbot                  = \n| chaplain               = \n| reader                 = \n| organistdom            = \n| director               = \n| organist               = \n| organscholar           = \n| chapterclerk           = \n| laychapter             = \n| warden                 = \n| flowerguild            = \n| musicgroup             = \n| parishadmin            = \n| serversguild           = \n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n}}\n\n'''Our Lady of Assumption Church'''  is a Roman Catholic church.It is the [[Parish]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]. And it has 7 Sub-Parishes.\n\n= History =\nHistory states that in 1979 there were 14 Catholic families in [[Pragasapuram]]. Initially Pragasapuram was the Sub-Parish of the Sathankulam Parish. In 15-08-1880, Our Lady of Assumption Chapel was opened by Fr.Denish Kushan. The first Car Procession of Our Lady of Assumption was held on 15-08-1895. At that time there was 3 Chapparam. Devotees carry it on their shoulders. In 1907, [[Arthur Margoschis]] (Father of Nazareth) presented the Holy Cross of Jesus Christ that he kept in his Prayer hall,\u00a0 to the Our Lady of Assumption Church, Pragasapuram. \n\nIn 1909, Pragasapuram became an independent Parish. Sub-Parishes separated from the [[Sathankulam]] and [[Punnaikayal]] Parishes were merged with the Pragasapuram Parish. The foundation stone for New Church was laid in 1913 by Fr.T.Michael. After the completion of the New Church foundation work, the Church building work was stopped. Thus the Holy Mass was conducted in the Old Our Lady of Assumption Chapel. Many years later the New Church was built and the New Church was opened by Bishop.Rev.Fr.Thomas on 21-11-1967.As the days went by, In 1975 during Fr.Cruz Mariyan period, Chapparam was replaced by Chariot. In the feasts that followed, the devotees\u00a0 celebrated the Annual Feast of Our Lady of Assumption by pulling the St.Mary's Chariot.\n\nSt. Mary's Kebi was built on 11-08-1980 at the site of the Old Our Lady of Assumption Chapel to commemorate the Century year (1880- 1980) of Our Lady of Assumption Chapel. The new Church altar was refurbished and the floors replaced with marbles when Fr.Jackson was a Parish Priest. In the 25th year of the construction of the St.Mary's Century Kebi, it was restored and renovated by Fr.A.S.Raja on 14-08-2007\n\n= Sub Parishes =\n\n1. Our Lady of Health Church, Madhavanam\n\n2. St.Joseph's Church, Kandhasamypuram\n\n3. Sacred Heart of Jesus Church, Pillayanmanai\n\n4. Our Lady of Lourdes Church, Udayarkulam\n\n5. Our Lady of Lourdes Church, Thoppur\n\n6. St. Antony's Church, Themankulam\n\n7. St. Antony's Church, Kurippankulam\n\n= Festivals =\n\n== St.Mary's Annual Feast ==\n\n[[File:Flag pole of olap.jpeg|thumb|right|Flagpole of Church]]\nThe Church Parish is celebrating the Our Lady of Assumption Annual Feast in a grand manner. St.Mary's Flag hoisting was held on 6 August every year. Followed by that they celebrating the festival for 10 days. 9th and 10th day of Feast is an Important day of Our Lady of Assumption.\n[[File:Olap chariot.jpeg|thumb|right|St.Mary's Chariot]]\nCar procession was held on 14th and 15 August every year. On 9th day of Feast Eucharistic Adoration service was held at the Church premises.On 10th day of Feast the Grand Holy Mass was held at the Church. Flag Lowering was held on end of the Feast (15 August Night).\n\n== Samabanthi ==\nChurch provides free food for all people thrice a year in following dates.\n\n1. First Saturday of May month\n\n2. 16 August\n\n3. 29 September\n\n== Christmas ==\nThey celebrate Christmas by conducting Carols and Holy Mass. They built a Christmas Crib inside the church that reminds the Birth of Jesus.\n\n== Easter == \nThey celebrate Easter by conducting a Holy Mass on 12:00 am.They placed a Resurrection of Jesus statue to reminds the Resurrection of Jesus.\n\n= Chapels = \n1. St. Mary's Chapel\n[[File:Arputha kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|St.Mary's Chapel]]\n2. St. Antony's Chapel\n[[File:Antony kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|St. Antony's Chapel]]\n3. St. Michael's Chapel\n[[File:Michael kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|St. Michael's Chapel]]\n4. Our Lady of Good Health Chapel \n[[File:Velankanni kebi.jpeg|thumb|right|Our Lady of Good Health Chapel]]\n\n= Schools =\nTotally 4 schools were managed by our Parish.\n\n1. St.Mary's Middle School, Pragasapuram \n\n2. St. Joseph Primary School, Kandasamipuram\n\n3. R.C. Primary School, Thoppur\n\n4. R.C. Primary School, Udayarkulam \n\n= Wedding Hall =\n\n[[File:Marys mahal.jpeg|thumb|right|St.Mary's Mahal]]\nIt was a long-standing desire of the Pragasapuram Parish peoples to have a Wedding Hall of our own. As a result, in 2003 the foundation work was started by Fr. Arul Jackson. Most.Rev.Bishop.Yuvon Ambrose laid the foundation stone for St. Mary's Mahal. The pillars were erected and the concrete work was completed in Fr.Arul Jackson period. During the period of Fr.A.S.Raja, the First Floor was completed. Fr. Antony Duglas completed the St. Mary's  Mahal project with his efforts. Afterwards, during St.Mary's Annual Feast on 15-08-2013 Most.Rev.Bishop.Yuvon Ambrose blessed the Mahal and Aachi Masala Founder Mr.A.D. Padmasingh Isac opened the St. Mary's Mahal.\n\n= Convent =\nServite Convent, Pragasapuram\n[[Category:Catholic Church]]\n\n= Reference =\n<ref>http://catholicchurches.in/directory/tuticorin-churches/our-lady-of-assumption-church-pragasapuram.htm  </ref>\n", "name_user": "Snowgift111", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSub Parishes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Our_Lady_of_Assumption_Church,_Pragasapuram"}
